Poverty and death in Indonesian Goldland
When Bardina Degei cooks dinner, she doesn't use a stove.
She rarely uses a pot.
In her wooden house in Enarotali, the capital of the Paniai reign in Indonesia's troubled province of Papua, the housewife usually puts a sweet potato - locally referred to as "nota" - right into the fireplace.
After half an hour, the charred tuber is removed and devoured with zealous, unwashed hands.
Degei sits on the clay floor - she has no furniture - where she also carries out her daily work, e.g. B. Clothes with cloudy water to wash from the nearby swamp.
A bucket in a roofless room serves as a latrine.
As the youngest of her husband's four wives, no fields were assigned to her.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: most villagers are unemployed, and many drink hard, and there are the soldiers here.
"Nobody dares to walk around the village after 5 p.m.," she says.
It is a rare glimpse into daily life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was taken in in 1969 after a disputed referendum in Indonesia, when only 1,026 elders were to vote by a public hand-up in front of the occupation forces.
An existing movement that stirred up for independence against Dutch rule quickly turned against the Jakarta government, which maintains control of the region and excludes foreign journalists or legal observers from it.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, with the independent part of Papua New Guinea comprising the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is as remote as it is dull. The trip includes a 90-minute flight from the provincial capital Jayapura to Nabire and then a morning 5-hour drive by rental car.
There is no public transport.
The city, with about 19,000 inhabitants, consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences, and corrugated metal roofs, which have been converted into various yellow-brown tones by rust.
Very few Indonesians have made their journey here, let alone journalists and virtually no foreigners.
Before Christian missionaries arrived, Mee Pago Papuans worshipped a god named Uga Tamee.
There have been other changes, too.
"We weren't used to wearing those clothes," Degei says, pointing to her lively, hand-woven turban, dark shirt and bright skirt.
“We used to have only leaves on our bodies.”
Papua is Indonesia's poorest province, where 28% of people live below the poverty line and have some of the worst infant mortality and literacy rates in Asia.
But it's also Indonesia's goldland.
The largest and most profitable gold mine in the world, Grasberg, owned by the Freeport McMoran from Phoenix, is located just 60 miles from Paniai, a highland province the size of New Jersey with 153,000 residents.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined US$3.1 billion in gold and copper.
In addition, Papua has timber resources worth an estimated US$78 billion.
However, these riches are a source of misery for the Papuas, ensuring that Indonesia's powerful military maintains a suffocating presence.
A 2005 investigation in the New York Times reported that Freeport paid local military personnel and units nearly US$20 million between 1998 and 2004, including up to US$150,000 to a single officer.
Papuan demands for greater autonomy threaten these golden goose and are treated mercilessly.
According to activists, more than 500,000 Papua have been killed and thousands have been raped, tortured and detained by the Indonesian military since 1969.
Mass killings in Papua's tribal highlands in the 1970's became genocide, according to the Asia Human Rights Commission.
In the region alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters last year.
"We Will Lose Everything," reads a 2016 report by the Archdiocese of Brisbane, which includes reports of atrocities from the previous year, such as unlawful executions and torture - rape and electric strikes are particularly popular, according to another report - and the brutal crackdown on peaceful demonstrations.
"It's difficult to count the number of casualties as incidents happen every week," says Andreas Harsono, Indonesia researcher for Human Rights Watch.
The screws have intensified as Papua's resources bring an influx of settlers from other parts of Indonesia.
The population of 3.5 million inhabitants of the province is 83% Christian, but the demographic development is changing as Muslim economic migrants come from the populous islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese Warung canteens sell fried chicken and gado gado, a mixed vegetable served with peanut sauce.
Local people fight to keep up here.
"The migrants have begun selling chickens and vegetables in the traditional market cheaper than the local Papua," explains Abeth You, a 24-year-old Paniai local who moved to the provincial capital Jayapura for work.
"It has cost the native Papua - the mom-mum [the women] of Papua - their market."
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, popularly known as Jokowi, promised to address the inequalities and violations of the law in Papua during his 2014 election campaign.
The former carpenter secured 27 of Papua's total of 29 districts - including Paniai - on his way to the presidential palace in Jakarta.
But little has changed in Papua, and today the locals feel betrayed.
"Our hearts are broken because we voted for Jokowi in 2014, with the expectation that he will fulfill our hopes, that justice will be restored," You says.
In fact, only two months after Jokowi's inauguration in October, Paniai suffered a low point.
On the 7. December 2014 was a group of 11 children outside singing Christmas carols outside a campfire in Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers broke through the darkness on a motorcycle.
The startled children told them to turn on their headlights.
One of the soldiers took offense to their tone and later came back with four soldiers, according to local pastor Yavedt Tebai.
The soldiers who had been drinking were chasing and beating the group with their rifle butts, victims and witnesses said.
Then one of the soldiers fired into the children's group.
One child, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, the building of the nearby government commission was set on fire and things escalated the next day.
About 1,000 young Papua men, women and children gathered on a football pitch outside the local police station and the military command centre to demand justice.
They carried ceremonial hunting bows and performed the Waita dance - running in a circle and imitating a bird song - of Papua's Mee Pago tribe.
Some protesters began hurling rocks at police and military posts.
When the mood was heated up, the soldiers were sent an order via an internal radio: "If the crowds resist more than three times, they shoot them dead," according to an official document from TIME, which was not released to local media.
Yeremias Kayame, 56, the head of the Kego Koto district of Enarotali, saw the looming danger and called for calm and urged the crowd to return home.
No one was in the mood to listen.
"When I turned around, I was suddenly shot in my left wrist," he told TIME on the porch of his colorfully painted wooden house.
Kayame still doesn't know who fired, but says the bullet came from the ranks of the soldiers gathered here.
"It was crowded, a lot of shots were fired," he adds.
The local man, Alfius Youw, was hit three times, according to his cousin, who witnessed the shootings.
"I ran to him and examined his body to make sure it was him," Yohanes, who, like many Indonesians, bears just one name, told TIME in a bleak mood.
"I saw he was dead ... I kissed him."
Papua Police Chief Inspector Yotje Mende told reporters that his officers only wanted to "secure" their station because it was under attack.
