"We want prosecution, we want cessation, we want healing, we want reconciliation, but first we have to get justice," he said.
"We cannot achieve healing and reconciliation until we receive justice."
A medical examiner puts a sheet over the body of one of the victims of the Moore Ford lynch on 27. July 1946.
According to FBI files obtained from the NBC News, more than 50 men from Monroe and surrounding counties were suspected in the lynching trial.
But no one has ever been charged.
Although the suspects have remained on the loose for decades, civil rights activists say the dual motivation for the lynch actions across the city has always been well known: politics and sex.
In April 1946, a Supreme Court decision allowed black citizens in Georgia to cast their votes for the first time in the pre-election campaign in the summer.
About the same time as the election, according to the FBI, black farm tenant Roger Malcom stabbed a white landowner, Barnett Hester, during a fight - allegedly because of a woman.
Brooks said the rumor had been in the city that Hester had slept with Malcom's wife, Dorothy, and that the baby she was wearing was not from her husband.
On the 25. July 1946, Loy Harrison, a prominent white landowner, paid 600 dollars to free Malcom from prison, according to the FBI.
He was escorted to prison by Dorothy and her cousins Mae Murray and George Dorsey.
But when they then moved away from prison and approached Moore's Ford Bridge, a lynch mob surrounded the car.
"As it turns out, it was Harrison who prepared and ordered the murders," concludes an FBI report.
