New results of Swedish asylum age assessment tests released
The latest findings of testing for asylum seekers in Sweden, which has undergone a new method of medical assessment of their age, show that more than 80 per cent of those tested are older than 18. But not everyone believes in the accuracy of these results.
The Swedish Agency for Forensic Medicine (Rättsmedicinalverket) has begun carrying out the tests last year.
They are to make the assessment of age more accurate during the asylum procedure after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migration Verket) was criticised for errors in assessing the correct age of some refugees who were minors.
To date, Migrationsverket has sent out 6,880 cases to be tested and the Forensic Medicine Agency now has the results of a total of 2,481 tests from mid-March to 31. July 2017 published.
Eighty percent (2002) were judged to be 18 or older, while in another 25 cases the Forensic Medicine Agency assessed that the person was "possibly 18 years or older."
In 432 cases, the conclusion was that the person is "possibly under 18 years old."
The tests are carried out only in cases where the age of the person is questioned.
According to Johan Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency, the results are consistent in the past few months.
"We don't see much difference in the statistics of the past few months, the numbers are pretty consistent," he told The Local magazine.
The high proportion of cases where the person was judged to be over 18 does not necessarily mean that the asylum seeker lied about his age.
In May, the agency released the results of 581 tests, saying there were 442 cases that "propose that the person examined was 18 years or older."
When the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet examined the 581 published results, she found that in 243 of these cases, the person had openly said that she would be 18 years old this year.
The method of medical age assessment, in which X-rays of wisdom teeth and MRI images of knee joints are taken, which are then analyzed by dentists and radiologists, have also been criticized in some areas.
A skeptic is the Karolinska Institute's endocrinologist Claude Marcus, whose work includes assessing human biological maturity to see if they went through puberty sooner or later than usual.
"I had reason to think about it, and I don't think the type of measurement should be used.
Judging the biological age in this way is very uncertain.
If we can't say it for sure, we shouldn't pretend we could," he told the Metro newspaper.
However, Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency defended the accuracy of the tests: "In general, you can say that the risk of incorrectly assessing a child as an adult is low.
The biggest risk is when the person is just below 18, in this case this is about 10 percent."
