Clubs are allowed to spend a lot of money on the acquisition of players, but must counteract with legitimate sources of revenue that allow them the break-even point in their football-related business.
FFP was conceived by Michel Platini after his election as UEFA president in 2007.
The former French player believed that clubs that had incurred enormous debts in their pursuit of success effectively cheated and risked ruining themselves if banks or owners withdrew their support.
In 2011, FFP shifted from the focus on clubs' debts to monitoring their losses.
The change meant that the business model that Roman Abramovich originally used in Chelsea in 2003 - bought a club with potential and then invested heavily to improve the squad and build a global brand - was to become a tougher affair.
During the current three-year FFP assessment period, which runs until 2018, clubs can accept losses of 30 million euros.
