Although PSG has paid the buy-out clause of Neymar in a lump sum, it can distribute the amount for the accounting over the duration of its contract.
Neymar has signed a five-year contract so that the transfer amount for the next five years can be reported in the annual financial statements.
The first wave of FFP sanctions in 2014 has hit the PSG along with Abu Dhabi, which is owned by Manchester City, with the heaviest sanctions.
The PSG received a fine of 60 million euros (at that time 82 million dollars), which was later reduced to 20 million euros - and it was ordered that the team members for the Champions League of the 2014/15 season remain limited to 21 players instead of the otherwise normal 25 players.
UEFA is looking for clubs that could try to outsmart their financial oversight by inflating their revenues through companies linked to the owners of a club.
While a Qatari company could sponsor the PSG if the value of sponsorship were to exceed the standard market rates, UEFA would not consider this a legitimate income.
That's exactly what happened in 2014, when UEFA decided that the value of the PSA's sponsorship was inflated by the Qatar Tourism Authority.
