NHS (The National Health Service) is to prescribe controversial HIV drug 10,000 people
Patients will be given access to "transformative" HIV prevention treatment from September after a fight before the High Court against funding the drug in the NHS.
NHS England announced that pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) taken before sexual intercourse, which can reduce the risk of infection in high-risk patients by around 86 per cent, is now being delivered by the health service over an initial three-year study for an estimated 10,000 people.
He agreed to fund the trial after the Court of Appeals upheld a Supreme Court ruling last year that the NHS had the authority to pay for the PrEP despite the claim that local authorities should fund it.
The move announced on Thursday was welcomed by NHS England chief executive Simon Stevens as an "important new intervention," while the National Aids Trust (NAT) called this a "decisive moment."
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to allow people to sign up, and more clinics will follow in October before it will be launched across England in April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a consequence of HIV supplements taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
Studies have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV transmission in those at risk of infection.
Taking PrEP before sexual intercourse means that there is just enough medication in a person’s body to prevent HIV infection.
Such medications can be taken every day or so already two hours before sexual intercourse.
Those eligible for treatment include gay or bisexual men, transsexuals, and individuals with HIV-positive partners who have not been successfully treated.
In clinics, appropriate participants who agree with the study, including men, women, transgender people, and individuals who have a partner whose HIV status is not known to be controlled by antiretroviral treatment, are identified.
People who live in England and are registered with a GP may also sign up for a possible participation in their local participating sex clinic.
The programme will be £10 million and NHS England signed a contract to supply the drugs this week following international competitive procurement.
The study is intended to assess the full potential of PrEP by collecting clinical evidence on a large scale, how it is targeted, recorded and implemented.
Stevens said: "This great new intervention should complement and overtake the far-reaching and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
It is another milestone in the more than three decades of progress in addressing one of humanity's biggest health challenges."
Deborah Gold, chief executive at NAT (National Aids Trust), said: "This is a pivotal moment in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, if it is specifically targeted at people in need and vulnerable, offers the opportunity to change the English HIV epidemic.
From September, people at high risk of HIV will have access to this NHS-funded attempt in England to develop a new tool that is truly individually controlled and not subject to negotiation with a partner, leading to the improvement of many, many lives.
We warmly welcome this announcement."
Ian Green, chief executive of the Terrence Higgins Trust, said: "The priority must now be that the study is conducted quickly across the country and that no one who is at risk for HIV is left behind.
Now that PrEP testing medicine has been procured, we are on track to protect more than 10,000 HIV-infected people."
Sharon Hodgson, shadow health minister, said: "The start of the PrEP process is welcome and overdue after months of delays and hesitant implementation by the government.
The evidence shows how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to HIV prevention and can stop the transmission of this life-changing infection.
This attempt brings us one step closer to understanding the benefits of PrEP.
Now it is important that this study is carried out as soon as possible across the country to protect individuals who are HIV-infected, and that it will help us get one step closer to ending the spread of HIV in society.
