In fact, when a company asks employees for your feedback, it can have an expectation that change is on the way.
And if the change doesn’t come fast enough, or not at all, this can breed disappointments and demotivate employees.
"If you ask for 4,000 suggestions, you need to be ready to have 4,000 conversations," said Russell Raath, president of consulting at business management firm Kotter International, which has seen companies that have relied too much on collecting data.
"Because if you don't follow, employees will wonder, "Did you really hear me?
Are you taking care of this?
And if you don't care, why should I? "
Madison Reed, who is now conducting monthly employee surveys, was able to initiate measures on the same day when a problem is reported about Glint, according to Errett.
And after gathering feedback from frustrated employees, she was able to reorganize multiple teams within the company and add a communication training to address the issues through the speed of decision-making and the quality of communication.
At Ruby Tuesday, the company is always getting new insights into employees, and it hopes that in the long run, this will lead to a better bonding of workers in an industry known for high sales.
"If you're not obliged to create a culture of transparency, you're going to lose people," Vitrano said.
"And if you lose people, you lose customers too.
