Military reforms in Turkey - Erdogan's fear of the army
Every year in early August, the Supreme Military Council (YAS) in Ankara discusses retirements and promotions in the Officers Corps.
So also this week.
At first glance, a normal process.
But nothing is routine in the Turkish armed forces a year after the coup attempt.
The meeting was no longer held in the building of the General Staff, as it used to be, but in the prime minister's office.
The five Deputy Prime Ministers and the Ministers for Defence, Home Affairs, Justice and Foreign Affairs have now also taken part in the discussions, chaired by the Head of Government.
Thus, the civilians in the YAS were in the majority.
The government is pulling the reins in the military.
Chief of Staff General Hulusi Akar remains in office, but the commanders of the army, the air forces and the navy have been deposed.
Since the failed coup, head of state Erdogan has fired 169 of the 326 generals and admirals.
Over 10,000 soldiers have been removed from the ranks of the army - mostly because of alleged links to the movement of exile preacher Fethullah Gülen, whom Erdogan sees as the mastermind of the coup attempt.
Against 486 people who are said to have been directly involved in the coup attempt, is being negotiated in Ankara since this week.
Already the day after the coup, Erdogan had described the attempted overthrow as a "gift of God" as he gave him the opportunity to "completely cleanse" the armed forces.
But does Erdogan really have the army under control?
At the end of February, the newspaper "Hürriyet" published an article with the headline "Unease in the military headquarters."
In the General Staff, there are concerns about an increasing "Islamization" of the army, which manifests itself, among other things, in the lifting of the headscarf ban for female soldiers, wrote the newspaper.
The big clean-up in the army and the security forces continues anyway.
In mid-July, Erdogan had another 7395 public servants fired by decree, including 2303 policemen and 546 soldiers.
It seemed as if Erdogan had tamed the military.
The generals used to be considered the actual masters of the country.
Three times they putthed, citing their role as guardians of the secular state order.
After his election victory in 2002, Erdogan pushed back the power of the military step by step, not least citing the reform requirements of the European Union.
Former officers say Erdogan is specifically pushing ahead with an Islamization of the armed forces.
In the magazine "Vocal Europe" warned an unnamed officer who sought asylum after the coup attempt for fear of persecution abroad, the Turkish army will be "full of extremists and Salafists" in a few years.
If this is true, such a development could not leave NATO cold.
In any case, there are doubts in the alliance after the purges about the readiness of the Turkish army.
The leadership structures and operational capabilities are "weakened," NATO diplomats say.
