GMB concern over investment in the McVitie factory in Glasgow
A union wants to make sure with managers of the biscuit manufacturer McVitie about the long-term commitment to production at their plant in Glasgow.
GMB Scotland said the company had remained silent about the future of investment at the Tollcross site.
More than 500 employees work at the plant, which manufactures Hobnobs and Rich Tea cookies alongside other products.
McVities owner Pladis said he has invested more than 5 million pounds in recent years.
He added that staff and union representatives would be "the first to know" if their activities were to change.
In a letter to the company's store manager, GMB called on Scotland McVitie's to "consider that funding for modernisation of production lines will not be driven forward."
GMB senior organizer Drew Duffy said: "The fact that we cannot gain clarity from the General Site manager about the business needs and investment plans for the future of Tollcross deeply affects our members.
Generations of families have worked here and the workforce is strongly focused on the local community and the Greater Glasgow area, an important pillar of decent employment in an area with high unemployment and social disadvantage.
Therefore, from the perspective of jobs, wages and prosperity, and against the backdrop of Brexit, the rising cost of living and the chronic decline in production, the eastern end of Glasgow urgently needs a thriving production presence at McVitie."
A spokeswoman for Pladis said: "The branch manager at Tollcross only received a letter from GMB Scotland yesterday, and the company will respond directly to this as we appreciate the continued commitment to staff and union representatives.
We had a regular meeting with staff and GMB representatives at Tollcross two months ago, where some questions were discussed openly.
We discussed with the employees that, like all companies operating in an extremely competitive and uncertain economic climate, we are constantly reviewing our business - and this applies to all our business units and locations - to remain competitive.
She added: "Over the past few years, we have invested more than 5 million pounds in our Tollcross site, particularly in production lines and operational improvements.
We fully recognize the legacy of Tollcross as a production facility. Should our operations at the site change, the employees and their union representatives will be the first to know this."
