Thus, the report comes to the very clear conclusion: "The fact that pupils and/or their environment who were affected in advance were entrusted to him could not be confirmed in the context of the investigation".
As for sexual abuse, Georg Ratzinger is therefore to be acquitted of any co-knowledge.
So he cannot be accused of not having prevented him or brought him to the attention of the complaint.
Therefore, there is no reason to associate his good name with these obnoxious crimes, as unfortunately happened in some cases.
In the media, much of "violence cesses" was to be read at the Regensburg Domspatzen.
The former cathedral chapel master Georg Ratzinger is accused in the report "looking away".
Does he have to live with this accusation?
Michael Hesemann: This is the big problem that everything was mixed and mixed in the reporting to a huge melange of sexual abuse and excesses of violence and somewhere, in the middle of it, Georg Ratzinger.
But that is exactly what abuse of the report is.
There is a clean separate: between the preschool and the high school of the Domspatzen, between sexual abuse and excesses of violence and, say, other accusations.
In addition, the report deals with incidents from the period since 1945, including from four decades in which Georg Ratzinger was not choir director of the Domspatzen.
All the terrible beating education, the cases in which boys were downright harassed and maltreated by sadistic teachers and suffered horribly, all occurred at the preschool in Etterzhausen and Pielenhofen, where really scandalous conditions must have prevailed.
But cathedral chapel master Georg Ratzinger had nothing to do with them, because he did not see the boys until they were already at the Domspatzengymnasium.
On which, as most witnesses point out, the topic of "preschool" was taboo.
One was only happy to have escaped her and enjoyed the so much better treatment and for many even "paradisiacal" conditions.
What was different at the Domspatzengymnasium?
Michael Hesemann: There was already discipline, but no sadistic violence.
And this also applies to Georg Ratzinger, in whom the report concludes that "many victims appreciated the general humanity of R. and therefore in numerous cases, despite violence, even connect positive memories with him".
So at most there is still the accusation of having looked away.
But despite all efforts, the report was only able to define two periods in which he was told about the conditions at the preschool.
The first time in 1970/71, when he was just beginning to establish himself and of the events at a school where he just did not work and was responsible, (so the witness) did not want to hear anything, and then only again around 1993.
Did Georg Ratzinger consistently close his ears before the conditions?
Michael Hesemann: No, because already in 1989 he wrote a letter to the director of the Domspatzengymnasium, which the report even reproduces.
