Even in the face of the danger of negative press releases, he recommended urgent intervention.
This was, of course, at a time when there was legal clarity when beating penalties were long prohibited in Bavaria.
Before that, they took place in a legal grey area, as each of us still knows.
It was also difficult for him to estimate where those affected might be exaggerated or dramatized and where the permissible limit had really been exceeded.
But you can't say he's always looked away.
That's just not true.
It was not until 1980 that the beating penalty at schools was officially abolished in Bavaria.
Princess Gloria von Thurn and Taxis claimed that it was unfair to apply today’s educational standards to the time.
How do you see that?
Michael Hesemann: We historians are talking about the "pitchwork of anachronism", i.e. the danger of evaluating the past by today's moral standards.
The princess is right.
But of course this does not apply to sexual abuse, which at all times was abhorrent and also not for what was committed in preschool in terms of reciprocities and violence against innocent children's souls, this goes far beyond what was usual at that time.
This is all terrible and I'm glad it's finally being worked up.
But at the same time I have to protect Georg Ratzinger, because all this had nothing to do with him.
His means of discipline and punishment, i.e. slapping and pulling on the hair and ears, were widespread in the 1970s.
When physical punishment was then banned, he also strictly adhered to it.
What picture of his time in Regensburg did Georg Ratzinger reproduce in the conversations with you for the book "My Brother the Pope"?
Did the issue of beatings also come up?
Michael Hesemann: Well, the book is about the life of his brother Joseph, Pope Benedict XVI, told from his perspective, since the Domspatzen played only a minor role.
Nevertheless, I do not hide the fact that he led a strict regiment there.
But even that must be said: Without this perfectionism, without the demand of unconditional discipline, it would hardly have been possible for him to form an institution of world rank from the previously more nationally known Regensburg Domspatzen, true cultural ambassadors of Europe and his musical tradition, who went on tour twice in the USA (1983 and 1987) and Japan (1988 and 1991).
With biscuits and candy alone, you don’t turn unruly boys into great singers and face every success, no matter what the field, but always discipline, passion and self-overcoming.
As a person you experienced Georg Ratzinger during the conversations about her book?
Michael Hesemann: By working on the book and beyond, I really got to know Georg Ratzinger quite well and experienced him again and again as a wonderful, humorous, basic, deeply believing and heartfelt person, of whom you cannot imagine that he could do even a fly a little offsee.
I regularly get involved, as many former cathedral sparrows still today, 23 years after his retirement, keep in touch with him, visit him, read him aloud - he is almost blind - and treat him like a member of their family.
Those who do not forgive him to this day that he was once strict with them are clearly in the minority.
Most of the cathedral sparrows are grateful to him today for enriching their lives and bringing them close to the world of music.
And that he was always a good, fatherly teacher - a strict father, certainly, that may be - but also a lovable respect person, to whom they still look up today and whom they worship.
And please, again quite clearly: everything that is accused of him are methods of education that were the order of the day at that time.
We can be glad we have overcome this time long ago.
But it's highly unfair, a man just because he's prominent and has an even more prominent brother, to make the media scapegoat.
There's all too obvious the evil intent behind it.
Because the report, which has just been published, exonerates him.
Now the decency would command, a 93-year-old man who has earned great merit and without whom outside Bavaria and perhaps still Germany probably no one would know the Regensburg Domspatzen, finally to leave in peace.
